# PROJECT BRIEF — Desire Escorts Rebuild (Next.js + Strapi)

## Project Context

Desire Escorts currently runs on WordPress/Elementor with Dutch and English content (`/` and `/en/`) on [desire-escorts.nl](https://desire-escorts.nl/).
Escort profiles (products) have already moved to Strapi and will remain the source of truth for profile data, profile content, and availability status.

The website will be rebuilt in a modern Next.js/Node.js stack with content optimization during migration to recover organic performance.

## Primary Goal

Rebuild the website in Next.js while **recovering and improving organic performance** through content optimization during migration. This approach was chosen based on:
- Evidence of traffic decline since September 2025
- Content audit revealing bloat, poor user intent alignment, and template duplication
- SEO/GEO/AEO analysis indicating current content patterns contributing to algorithmic penalties

## Migration Principle

- Launch phase = **optimize-during-build** migration:
  - Keep URLs stable (no slug changes without redirect mapping).
  - Optimize content structure to serve user intent immediately.
  - Reduce content bloat by 60-80% while preserving unique value.
  - Optimize metadata for CTR improvement.
  - Structure content for AI extraction (featured snippets, AI Overviews).
  - Preserve high-value internal linking pathways.
- Content optimization follows documented specifications:
  - `CONTENT_SPECIFICATIONS.mdc` for page-level structure
  - `KEYWORD_STRATEGY.mdc` for keyword targeting
  - `SEO_OPTIMIZATION_GUIDELINES.mdc` for SEO/GEO/AEO best practices

## Technical Direction

- Frontend: Next.js (Node.js runtime)
- CMS/Data source: Strapi
- Hosting and deployment: Vercel (preview + production environments)
- Delivery model: Git-based CI/CD with automated Vercel builds per branch/PR
- Legacy extraction sources:
  - WordPress export data
  - Firecrawl site extraction
  - XML sitemaps
  - Search Console performance data
- Content domains:
  - Core pages (optimized from legacy)
  - Page structure/content blocks (restructured per specifications)
  - Media assets
  - Blog content
  - Internal links (high-value pathways preserved)
  - URL topology (preserved)

## Scope

### In Scope (Phase 1)

- Rebuild NL and EN site architecture with URL preservation.
- Optimize all indexable pages following Content Specifications.
- Extract unique content from legacy, remove template filler.
- Optimize metadata for CTR and keyword targeting.
- Structure FAQs for schema markup and AI extraction.
- Integrate escort profile data and availability from Strapi.
- Preserve crawlability/indexability signals (canonicals, hreflang, high-value internal links).
- Implement schema markup (FAQ, LocalBusiness, Person).

### In Scope (Content Optimization)

- Word count reduction per page type specifications.
- Metadata optimization per Keyword Strategy.
- FAQ restructuring for AI extraction.
- Unique content creation for location/attribute pages.
- Removal of template boilerplate and filler content.

### Out of Scope (Phase 1)

- URL structure changes (URLs preserved from legacy)
- New page types not in current sitemap
- Major IA restructuring beyond content optimization
- Non-essential feature additions

## SEO Requirements (Non-Negotiable)

### URL Stability
- Exact URL preservation — no slug changes without redirect mapping.
- Keep language paths stable (`/` NL, `/en/` EN).
- No accidental deindexing of currently valuable pages.

### Content Optimization
- All pages optimized per Content Specifications.
- Word counts within specified limits per page type.
- Unique content sections required (no template-only pages).
- FAQs structured for FAQ schema markup.

### Metadata Optimization
- Meta titles optimized for CTR (50-60 chars, keyword front-loaded).
- Meta descriptions optimized with CTA intent (150-160 chars).
- H1 contains primary keyword naturally.

### Technical SEO
- Self-referencing canonical URLs.
- Correct hreflang implementation (NL/EN alternates).
- Schema markup per page type (FAQ, LocalBusiness, etc.).
- Preserve or improve Core Web Vitals.
- Preserve technical SEO behavior through deployment.

### Internal Linking
- Preserve high-value internal link pathways.
- Maintain hub-and-spoke structure from homepage.
- No broken internal links.

## Deployment and Environments

- Production deployment target is Vercel.
- Maintain separate preview and production environments for safe validation.
- Ensure environment variable strategy is defined for:
  - Strapi API access
  - analytics/search console integrations
  - any SEO/runtime feature flags
- Build pipeline must include pre-release SEO checks before production promotion.
- Rollback path must be documented and validated before launch.

## Content and Discovery Inputs

Migration discovery combines:

- XML sitemap inventory (URL scope)
- WordPress export datasets (structured legacy source)
- Firecrawl outputs (rendered content, link graph, FAQ extraction)
- Search Console data (keyword/page prioritization)
- Media extraction and mapping
- URL-level inventory + optimization manifest

## Expected Deliverables

- URL inventory (NL/EN) with migration status and keyword assignment
- Content optimization map (legacy → optimized structure per page type)
- Internal link preservation map
- Media inventory + replacement mapping
- Optimized content per Content Specifications
- Schema markup implementation
- Go-live SEO QA checklist and validation report

## Delivery Phases

1. **Discovery and Inventory** (Complete)
   - Crawl and export all relevant sources.
   - Build canonical URL inventory and classify by type.
   - Extract Search Console performance data.

2. **Strategy and Specifications** (Complete)
   - Define Content Specifications per page type.
   - Define Keyword Strategy and assignments.
   - Define SEO Optimization Guidelines.

3. **Build and Optimize**
   - Implement Next.js routes/templates.
   - Extract unique content from legacy per page.
   - Create optimized content per specifications.
   - Implement schema markup.

4. **SEO QA and Pre-Launch**
   - Validate content against specifications.
   - Validate metadata optimization.
   - Validate schema markup.
   - Validate internal links.
   - Validate technical SEO (canonical, hreflang, robots).

5. **Launch and Monitor**
   - Monitor indexing, rankings, traffic, crawl stats, and 404s.
   - Compare performance vs. pre-migration baseline.
   - Identify pages needing further optimization.

## Success Criteria

- All in-scope legacy URLs live with optimized content.
- Content follows specifications (word counts, structure, unique sections).
- Metadata optimized per Keyword Strategy.
- FAQ schema implemented on applicable pages.
- NL/EN routing preserved.
- Internal link pathways maintained.
- No critical SEO regressions in indexation/crawlability signals at launch.
- Escort profile + availability powered by Strapi in production.
- Performance recovery signals visible within 3 months (position/CTR improvement for priority keywords).

## Risks to Manage

- Content optimization removing ranking content (mitigated by preserving unique content, only removing filler)
- Metadata changes hurting CTR (mitigated by A/B monitoring post-launch)
- Internal link equity loss (mitigated by preserving high-value pathways)
- Media mismatches or broken references
- Hreflang/canonical implementation inconsistencies
- Unexpected Strapi schema/content gaps during integration

## Governance

- Content optimization must follow documented specifications (Content Specifications, Keyword Strategy, SEO Guidelines).
- URL changes require explicit approval and redirect mapping.
- Deviations from specifications require documented justification.
- Post-launch performance monitoring informs further optimization.

